segments.text: I remember when we were sophomores, there were three of us in a room, Dummy McLaren, Hudson Van Lone, and I.
And Dummy was a real prankster.
And one time, and everybody in the battery knew that Dummy was.
And one time, the seniors were having a meeting in the captain's room, and Dummy
tied a rope on the door handle and affixed it to another door handle.
And then he threw a huge firecracker through the transom into the middle of this meeting.
And it took the seniors some time to come to break that door down, but they immediately came to our room and Dummy was acting innocently, reading a magazine on his bunk.
And they just grabbed him, they knew who it was, and dragged him out and we heard the boards popping.
And nobody was hurt?
Nobody was hurt, right.
Former students, faculty, friends, advisors, to what Aggies do you feel the greatest depths of gratitude now?
Of my own self.
To whom are you most grateful for what they did for you in shaping your life?
I would think Coach Anderson, character builder, track team coach.
J.P. Abbott, English professor, tennis coach.
John Reed, basketball coach.
And Harold Vance, who was the head of the Petroleum Engineering Department.
I think those four people had as much influence on me and them as anybody.
Do you remember going to any of those people or anyone else and getting some truly meaningful advice, something that you realize now?
Yes, I think Harold Vance.
Going to him and talking to him about my future in the petroleum industry and advice he gave me.
And I think it's probably been the
Also, I'd say J.P. Abbott, in talking to him, I had always been interested in writing, and so
I have, the writing has been, I've done a number of, I have a consulting business, and in doing consulting reports, writing is very important.
I think the basics I learned on the applet have been very helpful.
I and two other guys also wrote a book called The Dynamic Natural Gas Industry, which was published by the University of Oklahoma Press.
I'd say the basest thing I learned under Alpert have been contributed to that.
And you never had a situation that some of us had where you were going down this direction academically and you changed your course and went another direction.
No, I never have.
I knew what I was aiming for and have been on that road ever since.
What have we overlooked?
What have we not mentioned that we should have?
I think maybe the subject of women at A&M, we mentioned it, but I was very much opposed to women being admitted to A&M.
And I realize now that I was wrong, that the
the one thing you didn't learn at A&M, I'd say, was relationship with women.
And that was the one thing A&M didn't put.
And when I was there, there were daughters of professors could go there, and there were six daughters that
were in school at that time.
How were they treated?
Oh, like queens, of course.
But I'd say the, of course, the admittance of women to A&M has made A&M come from a very special military school to a first rate financial, a first rate educational institution.
Now, that discussion was almost 40 years ago.
Right.
Why were you at that time opposed to coeducation?
I thought it would break down the
the bonding that existed and which accounted for so many great military guys from A&M.
And I thought that at that time I wanted to see A&M
continue as a first-rate military academy with a first-rate educational curriculum.
Have you had any family members or children of dear friends who've been A&M coeds?
No.
No, I haven't.
My daughter went to Rollins.
One of my daughters went to Rollins.
And another daughter went to Texas Tech.
But the one who went to Rollins in Florida, they had no football team down there.
And she is bigger than I am.
And I burned out my wife
But when I was president of the association, because having to go to all these different events, my wife finally said, you know, I've just had enough.
And so my daughter, eldest daughter, has gone to these different A&M things.
I enjoyed telling the story when, in the same place, in an interview with Billy Clayton, he indicated he had been opposed to coeducation also, and I said, why?
And he said, I thought that the women would kill the A&M spirit.
Right, right, same here.
I said, you're kidding.
He said, no, I'm serious.
And then he said, well, do the Aggie women have any pride?
And I said, sir, as far as I can tell, the coeds now have more pride maybe than the males do.
He said, good, because I've got three granddaughters there.
How do you feel about A&M's progress now?
I think it's excellent.
I think the progress is excellent.
I've kept up with A&M by going to various meetings and so forth, and I think the progress is excellent.
I do think that the bonfire incident sort of shook up everything for a while.
But I think that it's very important as to who the new president is.
Last question then.
What feelings do you carry in your heart for Texas A&M?
One of great love and devotion.
You know, it's similar to my feelings for my church and my family.
As a matter of fact, I have planned my own funeral, and in the funeral I've asked that certain things be played.
Amazing grace.
Here I am, Lord.
And the Aggie War Hymn, I've asked them to play that.
Let's quit on that.
Tell me about any of the conversations you remember of the former student officers about co-education and non-compulsory core before you resigned as president.
Well, the reason I resigned was to run for governor.
But had the former student leadership talked about those topics yet?
Well, let's see.
Well, actually, I remember
I remember Wofford Cain, who was on the Development Fund Board, he was very much opposed to admitting women.
And actually, most of my classmates were opposed to admitting women, just in talking to them.
I don't remember the
But I think as I told you, John Lindsay told me that he would never forgive me because when I resigned to run for governor, he became the president.
And at the first association meeting, Earl Rudder said, John, I want you to make a motion to admit women.
And John said, what?
He said, make a motion, John.
Did you know that that was coming up when you?
No, I didn't.
I didn't know that.
So the board, the association board had not discussed that?
No, they didn't know that.
And John said that
He made the motion, and he said, all in favor say aye, and there were only two or three ayes.
All opposed say no, and there was a thunderous number of noes.
And he hit the gavel and said, the ayes have it.
And that's how women were admitted to A&M.
And as I understand it, then they went down the hallway.
and told the, they were then called directors, now regents, that the former student had adopted that.
I see.
I didn't know that.
That's what I understood that they did.
But this had not been a subject of big discussion.
No, it hadn't at that time.
You know, there was not planned anything, but people were, most of the people I knew were opposed to it.
